{"vocabInfos":[{"lsjDefs":"<b> λόγ-ιος</b>, α, ον, <br /> (λόγος) <b>of</b> or <b>belonging to</b> λόγοι: <br /><Level2><b>__I</b></Level2> <b>versed in tales</b> or <b>stories</b> (compare λόγος see), λόγιοι καὶ ἀοιδοί [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “P.” 1.94, compare “N.” 6.45: hence of chroniclers (opposed to poets), Περσέων οἱ λόγιοι 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 1.1 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; Αἰγυπτίων -ώτατοι [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. author] 2.3, compare 4.46 \">Refs</a>]; so later, οἱ - ώτατοι τῶν ἀρχαίων συγγραφέων [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 2nd c.BC: Polybius Historicus 6.45.1, compare 38.6.1, 1st c.BC: Diodorus Siculus Historicus 2.4, 1st c.BC: Dionysius Halicarnassensis 5.17, etc. \">Refs 2nd c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__I.2</b></Level3> generally, <b>learned, erudite</b>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 3rd c.AD: Democritus Epigrammaticus 30, etc.; λ. περὶ τὴν ὅλην φύσιν 4th c.BC: Aristoteles Philosophus “Politica” 1267b28 \">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]; ὁ λ. Ἀκεστῖνος, of a <b>learned</b> physician, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 3rd c.AD: Heliodorus Scriptor Eroticus 4.7 \">Refs 3rd c.AD+</a>]; οἱ -ώτατοι Τυρρηνῶν, of the Tuscan haruspices, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 1st-2nd c.AD: Plutarchus Biographus et Philosophus “Sulla” 7; Χαλδαίων οἱ λ. 2nd c.AD: Arrianus Historicus “Anabasis” 7.16.5, compare 1st c.AD: Josephus Historicus “Antiquitates Judaicae” 17.6.2, etc.\">Refs 1st c.AD+</a>]; λογιώτατος as title, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" “OGI” 408.5 (Theb. Aeg.), “POxy.” 902.1 (5th c.AD), etc.\">Refs 5th c.AD+</a>]; ὁ τῆς λ. μνήμης σχολαστικός [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" “PMasp.” 118.30 (6th c.AD). \">Refs 6th c.AD+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__II</b></Level2> <b>skilled in words, eloquent</b>, τὸ μεγαλοπρεπὲς ὅπερ νῦν καὶ λόγιον ὀνομάζουσιν [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th c.BC: Demetrius Phalereus Rhetor “Demetrius on Style” 38, etc.; 4th c.BC: Aristoteles Philosophus \">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>] is said to have made [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-3rd c.BC: Theophrastus Philosophus [τὸν] -ώτατον (of his disciples), 1st c.BC-1st c.AD: Strabo Geographus 13.2.4; λ. ἐξ ἀφώνου γενόμενος 1st-2nd c.AD: Plutarchus Biographus et Philosophus “Pompeius” 51 \">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]; epithet of Hermes, as the god of eloquence, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 2nd c.AD: Lucianus Sophista “Apol.” 2, “Gall.” 2 (_superlative_), 4th c.AD: Julianus Imperator “Orationes” 4.132a; οἱ λ. θεοί [prev. author] “Ep.” 80 \">Refs 2nd c.AD+</a>]; this sense is condemned by [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 2nd c.AD: Phrynichus Atticista 176\">Refs 2nd c.AD+</a>]. <i>adverb</i> -ίως <b>eloquently</b>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 1st-2nd c.AD: Plutarchus Biographus et Philosophus 2.405a\">Refs 1st c.AD+</a>]; ὡς ἐνῆν -ώτατα <b>as nearly in words as possible</b>, of the elephant, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\"[prev. work]968d. \">Refs</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__III</b></Level2> <b>oracular</b>, Ἀπόλλωνος δῶμα λόγιον [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" “Berl.Sitzb.” 1911.632 (from Cyprus). \">Refs</a>]","strongNumber":"G3052","accentedUnicode":"λόγιος","relatedNos":[{"strongNumber":"G0945","matchingForm":"βαττολογέω","stepTransliteration":"battologeō","gloss":"to babble","_zh_tw_Gloss":"用許多重複話","_es_Gloss":"balbucear","_zh_Gloss":"用许多重复话"},{"strongNumber":"G1351","matchingForm":"δίλογος","stepTransliteration":"dilogos","gloss":"insincere","_zh_tw_Gloss":"一口兩舌","_es_Gloss":"insincero ","_zh_Gloss":"一口两舌"},{"strongNumber":"G3051","matchingForm":"λόγιον","stepTransliteration":"logion","gloss":"oracles","_zh_tw_Gloss":"聖言","_es_Gloss":"oráculo","_zh_Gloss":"圣言"},{"strongNumber":"G3053","matchingForm":"λογισμός","stepTransliteration":"logismos","gloss":"thought","_zh_tw_Gloss":"思念, 計謀","_es_Gloss":"pensamiento","_zh_Gloss":"思念, 计谋"},{"strongNumber":"G3056","matchingForm":"λόγος","s